WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.449 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.449 --> 00:00:04.347 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.347 --> 00:00:05.796 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.796 --> 00:00:11.420 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:15.700 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So one of the
things I want to focus on today,

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:20.840 align:middle line:84%
and we'll get to this in just a
minute, is how to write a proof.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:30.410 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to be how to
write a mathematical proof.

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:40.360 align:middle line:90%


00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:44.400 align:middle line:84%
So how do you write a
proof, as opposed to,

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:49.570 align:middle line:84%
how do you think about why
something should be true?

00:00:49.570 --> 00:00:52.760 align:middle line:84%
And so this is one of
the important topics

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:54.800 align:middle line:90%
for this course.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:01:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So overall-- I mean, there's
a lot of important concepts

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:02.180 align:middle line:90%
that we will talk about.

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:04.760 align:middle line:84%
But some of the general
things that we will learn

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:06.960 align:middle line:84%
is how to prove
something, but also

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:10.170 align:middle line:84%
how to write a proper
mathematical proof.

00:01:10.170 --> 00:01:12.587 align:middle line:84%
And those things are a
little bit different.

00:01:12.587 --> 00:01:14.170 align:middle line:84%
And we'll talk about
this in a minute.

00:01:14.170 --> 00:01:16.960 align:middle line:90%


00:01:16.960 --> 00:01:19.580 align:middle line:90%
I also want to say that--

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:23.520 align:middle line:84%
so on the course information,
the last page of the course--

00:01:23.520 --> 00:01:25.480 align:middle line:84%
several people were
asking about this.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:31.720 align:middle line:84%
On the last page of course
information, there is--

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:33.140 align:middle line:90%
so there's the notes.

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:35.760 align:middle line:84%
There's the notes for
the class that I write.

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:38.280 align:middle line:84%
And I typically-- I try
to write them in advance,

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:39.620 align:middle line:90%
a couple of days in advance.

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:42.960 align:middle line:84%
And then I try to go
over it the day, also,

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:46.260 align:middle line:84%
to make sure to find typos
and things like that,

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:48.800 align:middle line:90%
so that it's more readable.

00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:53.160 align:middle line:84%
So if I were you, I would
first read the lecture notes

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:55.880 align:middle line:90%
that I post after the lectures.

00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:59.030 align:middle line:84%
And then there's also-- on
the last page of the course

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:01.470 align:middle line:90%
information, there is--

00:02:01.470 --> 00:02:03.730 align:middle line:90%
and I try to do this in advance.

00:02:03.730 --> 00:02:06.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's a little bit
difficult to do it in advance.

00:02:06.150 --> 00:02:10.830 align:middle line:90%
So it says the date.

00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:16.210 align:middle line:84%
And it says some key words
from the lecture on that date.

00:02:16.210 --> 00:02:20.510 align:middle line:84%
So over the weekend, I posted
it for the two lectures

00:02:20.510 --> 00:02:22.950 align:middle line:90%
for this week.

00:02:22.950 --> 00:02:24.450 align:middle line:90%
But then I go back--

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:25.890 align:middle line:90%
I will try to go back.

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:29.190 align:middle line:84%
So I actually went back this
morning and changed some of it

00:02:29.190 --> 00:02:32.510 align:middle line:84%
from the second lecture
so that it fits more.

00:02:32.510 --> 00:02:34.550 align:middle line:90%
And I think I will only--

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:38.350 align:middle line:84%
I give references
there to the book.

00:02:38.350 --> 00:02:42.310 align:middle line:84%
And initially, I was thinking of
giving both references to Rudin

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:45.830 align:middle line:90%
and to the main textbook.

00:02:45.830 --> 00:02:47.550 align:middle line:90%
I think it's probably just--

00:02:47.550 --> 00:02:51.910 align:middle line:84%
maybe it's-- I think it's
probably smarter just to give it

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:53.040 align:middle line:90%
from the main textbook.

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:56.070 align:middle line:90%


00:02:56.070 --> 00:03:00.190 align:middle line:90%
And Rudin is a great book.

00:03:00.190 --> 00:03:09.310 align:middle line:84%
This was a book that was
created here a long time ago.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:12.610 align:middle line:84%
And it is a classic
in the subject.

00:03:12.610 --> 00:03:13.990 align:middle line:90%
It's a great book.

00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:16.250 align:middle line:84%
It's more formal
than the other book.

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:22.390 align:middle line:84%
So the other book is a
little bit more accessible.

00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.390 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why
we're using that.

00:03:24.390 --> 00:03:27.750 align:middle line:84%
But actually, Rudin
is a fantastic book.

00:03:27.750 --> 00:03:32.070 align:middle line:84%
If it was just
myself, I would just--

00:03:32.070 --> 00:03:34.170 align:middle line:90%
I think Rudin is hard to beat.

00:03:34.170 --> 00:03:37.410 align:middle line:84%
But the other one
is more accessible.

00:03:37.410 --> 00:03:40.030 align:middle line:84%
And so it might actually
be better the first time

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:40.850 align:middle line:90%
you learn it.

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:44.150 align:middle line:90%


00:03:44.150 --> 00:03:47.230 align:middle line:84%
So I think, from here
on out-- so I deleted

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:49.490 align:middle line:90%
the references I had to Rudin.

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:52.150 align:middle line:84%
I think I will just give
references to the main textbook.

00:03:52.150 --> 00:03:55.150 align:middle line:90%


00:03:55.150 --> 00:03:57.990 align:middle line:84%
But I certainly encourage
you to look at Rudin also.

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:02.910 align:middle line:84%
I also encourage you to look
at chapters that we will skip.

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:06.030 align:middle line:84%
But there's also things
that we initially skip,

00:04:06.030 --> 00:04:09.270 align:middle line:90%
and then we come back to.

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:12.030 align:middle line:90%
But again, you should--

00:04:12.030 --> 00:04:15.550 align:middle line:84%
it's like the-- when I
list the things that we

00:04:15.550 --> 00:04:17.950 align:middle line:84%
will cover in the
lecture in advance,

00:04:17.950 --> 00:04:21.730 align:middle line:84%
it's only a sort
of approximation.

00:04:21.730 --> 00:04:27.670 align:middle line:84%
So once I write the lecture,
it might be slightly different.

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:29.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:29.510 --> 00:04:33.490 align:middle line:84%
So we had-- so last time, we
talked about the theorem--

00:04:33.490 --> 00:04:35.030 align:middle line:90%
we didn't prove it--

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:43.120 align:middle line:84%
that the reals is a
complete ordered field.

00:04:43.120 --> 00:04:48.590 align:middle line:90%


00:04:48.590 --> 00:04:52.580 align:middle line:84%
And so, in particular,
it was an ordered set

00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:55.780 align:middle line:90%
that was also a field.

00:04:55.780 --> 00:04:57.120 align:middle line:90%
And it was complete.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:59.120 align:middle line:84%
And so, again,
"complete" meant--

00:04:59.120 --> 00:05:06.340 align:middle line:84%
so if you had a subset A
here, which was a subset of R,

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.250 align:middle line:90%
then A is bounded--

00:05:08.250 --> 00:05:10.940 align:middle line:90%


00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:29.660 align:middle line:84%
is bounded from above
if there exists M in R

00:05:29.660 --> 00:05:43.510 align:middle line:84%
such that for all a in A, a
here is less than or equal to M.

00:05:43.510 --> 00:05:46.220 align:middle line:84%
And then, if that's
the case, then we

00:05:46.220 --> 00:06:08.920 align:middle line:84%
say that an M here is said
to be an upper bound for A.

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:21.380 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, if A here
is a subset of R,

00:06:21.380 --> 00:06:39.660 align:middle line:84%
then we say that A
is bounded from below

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:59.620 align:middle line:84%
if there exists little m in R
such that m here is less than a

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:00.520 align:middle line:90%
for all a.

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:05.930 align:middle line:90%


00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:09.160 align:middle line:84%
So this is upper and
lower bounds, OK?

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:10.820 align:middle line:90%
And several people ask--

00:07:10.820 --> 00:07:14.420 align:middle line:90%
on Piazza, they ask--

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:21.820 align:middle line:84%
they were a little
unclear about,

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:26.320 align:middle line:84%
where does this M, capital M,
where does this have to be?

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:28.380 align:middle line:90%
In what set does it have to be?

00:07:28.380 --> 00:07:31.980 align:middle line:84%
And likewise for
this little m, right?

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:34.560 align:middle line:84%
And so let me try to
give you some example.

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:36.160 align:middle line:84%
And I tried to do
that on Piazza.

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:38.020 align:middle line:90%
But let me just--

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:40.080 align:middle line:84%
because several people
were asking about it,

00:07:40.080 --> 00:07:42.060 align:middle line:90%
let me just say again.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:46.320 align:middle line:84%
So this capital M, when
you have it like this,

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:51.250 align:middle line:84%
this capital M does not need
to be in the set, right?

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:52.270 align:middle line:90%
A is bounded.

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:53.180 align:middle line:90%
So here's an example.

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:56.690 align:middle line:90%


00:07:56.690 --> 00:08:01.690 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking at the set,
0, 1-- so this is the interval.

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:02.770 align:middle line:90%
This is the interval.

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:05.890 align:middle line:90%
But it does not contain 0.

00:08:05.890 --> 00:08:07.530 align:middle line:90%
And it does not contain 1.

00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:12.610 align:middle line:84%
But it contains everything
in between 0 and 1.

00:08:12.610 --> 00:08:14.670 align:middle line:90%
This one here is bounded.

00:08:14.670 --> 00:08:21.930 align:middle line:84%
So if this has A, and we think
about A here as a subset of R,

00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:23.700 align:middle line:90%
then A is bounded.

00:08:23.700 --> 00:08:27.010 align:middle line:90%


00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:31.530 align:middle line:84%
And so one usually says
it's bounded if it's

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:32.980 align:middle line:90%
both from above and below.

00:08:32.980 --> 00:08:43.250 align:middle line:90%


00:08:43.250 --> 00:08:45.630 align:middle line:84%
So if one just says
that it's bounded,

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:49.930 align:middle line:84%
then one means that it's
bounded from above and below.

00:08:49.930 --> 00:08:50.590 align:middle line:90%
It's bounded.

00:08:50.590 --> 00:08:53.470 align:middle line:90%


00:08:53.470 --> 00:08:56.240 align:middle line:84%
And so, because I
bounded from above--

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:01.170 align:middle line:90%


00:09:01.170 --> 00:09:04.690 align:middle line:84%
above, because you can just--
you have that if x here

00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:07.410 align:middle line:84%
is in this interval,
then, of course,

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:09.990 align:middle line:84%
x is less than or
equal to 1, right?

00:09:09.990 --> 00:09:15.410 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it's strictly
less than 1, right?

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:17.970 align:middle line:84%
But you see, this
set here, there

00:09:17.970 --> 00:09:24.370 align:middle line:84%
is no element in this set that
is an upper bound for this set,

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:25.250 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:27.990 align:middle line:84%
The upper bound is
outside the set.

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:30.970 align:middle line:84%
But it is in all of
R. And that's fine.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:37.430 align:middle line:84%
An upper bound will typically
just be in the larger set.

00:09:37.430 --> 00:09:43.570 align:middle line:90%
And the same with lower bound.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:48.250 align:middle line:84%
Now, this-- everything on this
board except this theorem--

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:50.942 align:middle line:84%
but this is in terms
of ordered sets.

00:09:50.942 --> 00:09:52.810 align:middle line:90%
It has nothing to do--

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:56.930 align:middle line:84%
it's just much more general
than R. So if you take--

00:09:56.930 --> 00:10:06.050 align:middle line:84%
if S here is an ordered set,
and A here is a subset--

00:10:06.050 --> 00:10:09.178 align:middle line:90%


00:10:09.178 --> 00:10:14.530 align:middle line:84%
is a subset-- so
it's an ordered set.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:18.970 align:middle line:90%
So it's a set with an ordering.

00:10:18.970 --> 00:10:25.050 align:middle line:84%
And if A here is a subset
of S, then, again, we

00:10:25.050 --> 00:10:45.170 align:middle line:84%
can say that A is bounded
from above if there exists M--

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:50.170 align:middle line:84%
again, M does not
have to be in A.

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:52.390 align:middle line:84%
But it can be just
in a larger set,

00:10:52.390 --> 00:11:06.390 align:middle line:84%
so that-- such that for all a
in A, it's less or equal to M.

00:11:06.390 --> 00:11:12.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is like the definition
in general, being bounded above,

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:17.010 align:middle line:84%
if you have a ordered set,
and you have a subset.

00:11:17.010 --> 00:11:19.170 align:middle line:90%
And now, just to illustrate it.

00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:23.970 align:middle line:84%
So typically, we're going to
think about where the set is

00:11:23.970 --> 00:11:26.170 align:middle line:90%
R with the usual ordering.

00:11:26.170 --> 00:11:28.030 align:middle line:90%
And you have a subset of it.

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:32.410 align:middle line:84%
And you talk about whether it's
bounded from above or below.

00:11:32.410 --> 00:11:34.170 align:middle line:84%
But of course, you
could also do it

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:37.390 align:middle line:84%
in a more general
setting like this.

00:11:37.390 --> 00:11:43.600 align:middle line:84%
And so here's an example, that
if you look at-- which maybe is

00:11:43.600 --> 00:11:45.360 align:middle line:90%
counterintuitive--

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:53.640 align:middle line:84%
but if you take-- if S
here is the half line,

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:57.120 align:middle line:90%
so it's all the real numbers--

00:11:57.120 --> 00:12:02.140 align:middle line:84%
it's between, say,
0 and infinity.

00:12:02.140 --> 00:12:05.720 align:middle line:90%


00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:12.120 align:middle line:90%
And then you'll have A here.

00:12:12.120 --> 00:12:16.050 align:middle line:90%
It's a subset, 0 to 1.

00:12:16.050 --> 00:12:21.936 align:middle line:90%


00:12:21.936 --> 00:12:27.500 align:middle line:84%
Now, A here, and the ordering--
so this is, of course,

00:12:27.500 --> 00:12:30.480 align:middle line:84%
a subset of R. But
you should forget

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:33.840 align:middle line:84%
about R. I mean, you
know the ordering from R.

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:36.600 align:middle line:84%
But forget about it,
because this is now what you

00:12:36.600 --> 00:12:40.600 align:middle line:90%
think about the set S, right?

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:45.840 align:middle line:84%
And so, if you're looking A as
a subset of this, then A here--

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:47.410 align:middle line:90%
A is bounded from above.

00:12:47.410 --> 00:12:55.920 align:middle line:90%


00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:56.420 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:12:56.420 --> 00:13:02.040 align:middle line:84%
This is just because,
for all A in A, you have

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:05.280 align:middle line:84%
that A here is
strictly less than 1.

00:13:05.280 --> 00:13:10.120 align:middle line:84%
So 1 here is an upper
bound for A, right?

00:13:10.120 --> 00:13:18.040 align:middle line:84%
But now, think about, does this
set here have a lower bound?

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:23.740 align:middle line:84%
Well, a lower bound have
to be inside this set, S,

00:13:23.740 --> 00:13:25.920 align:middle line:84%
because we're thinking
about this here

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:28.540 align:middle line:90%
as a subset of this ordered set.

00:13:28.540 --> 00:13:32.000 align:middle line:84%
We don't think about it as
a subset of the real line.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.840 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about it as
a subset of this set here,

00:13:36.840 --> 00:13:40.760 align:middle line:84%
then there is no lower
bound, because 0 is not

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:44.540 align:middle line:84%
in this set, and no negative
numbers in this set.

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:47.320 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- and
this seems maybe

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:49.040 align:middle line:90%
a little bit counterintuitive.

00:13:49.040 --> 00:14:08.790 align:middle line:84%
But A is not bounded from below
as a subset of S. Obviously,

00:14:08.790 --> 00:14:11.040 align:middle line:84%
it is bounded from below if
you were thinking about it

00:14:11.040 --> 00:14:13.500 align:middle line:90%
as a subset of a real line.

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:16.040 align:middle line:84%
But if you think about
it as a subset of S,

00:14:16.040 --> 00:14:19.600 align:middle line:90%
it's not bounded from below.

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:20.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:31.760 align:middle line:84%
So another person was asking
the infinite and minus infinity.

00:14:31.760 --> 00:14:35.830 align:middle line:90%
Those are not real numbers, OK?

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:36.565 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:14:36.565 --> 00:14:38.190 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So on the
homework, should we

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:41.593 align:middle line:84%
consider all of the
things as subsets of R?

00:14:41.593 --> 00:14:42.510 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Sorry?

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:47.270 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: For question 3
on the homework [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:52.470 align:middle line:90%
they're all subsets of R.

00:14:52.470 --> 00:14:56.050 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: If it's
not directly stated that--

00:14:56.050 --> 00:15:01.550 align:middle line:84%
if it's not directly stated
that there's a set, S, and then

00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:04.830 align:middle line:84%
it has to be a
subset of that set,

00:15:04.830 --> 00:15:09.270 align:middle line:84%
then it would be assumed
that it's a-- yeah.

00:15:09.270 --> 00:15:13.870 align:middle line:84%
Of course, you are
welcome to ask on Piazza.

00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:15.590 align:middle line:90%
I don't have the homework here.

00:15:15.590 --> 00:15:17.670 align:middle line:84%
But I would say
that you're safe--

00:15:17.670 --> 00:15:22.510 align:middle line:84%
if it's not stated directly
what the larger set is, then

00:15:22.510 --> 00:15:24.350 align:middle line:84%
you can assume it's
R, because we're going

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:25.890 align:middle line:90%
to concentrate mostly on R.

00:15:25.890 --> 00:15:29.350 align:middle line:84%
This is another
distinction between Rudin

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:32.090 align:middle line:84%
and this book that
is the main textbook.

00:15:32.090 --> 00:15:37.590 align:middle line:84%
Rudin is more abstract than
the main textbook we are using.

00:15:37.590 --> 00:15:42.890 align:middle line:84%
In particular, the
main textbook here,

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:44.890 align:middle line:84%
and I'll do the
same in my lectures,

00:15:44.890 --> 00:15:47.910 align:middle line:84%
is that a lot of things
are motivated from R.

00:15:47.910 --> 00:15:50.550 align:middle line:84%
And then you
abstract afterwards,

00:15:50.550 --> 00:15:53.990 align:middle line:84%
so whereas Rudin starts
with the abstraction,

00:15:53.990 --> 00:15:58.390 align:middle line:84%
and then it specializes to
R. And of course, there's

00:15:58.390 --> 00:16:01.880 align:middle line:84%
an argument for maybe starting
with the familiar and then

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:03.880 align:middle line:84%
abstract, instead of doing
the other way around.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:10.510 align:middle line:90%


00:16:10.510 --> 00:16:13.830 align:middle line:84%
And so for a-- whether
it's just an ordered set--

00:16:13.830 --> 00:16:19.250 align:middle line:84%
I mean, just in general, so
remember that completeness--

00:16:19.250 --> 00:16:23.950 align:middle line:90%


00:16:23.950 --> 00:16:28.910 align:middle line:84%
so completeness-- so this is
when you have an ordered set.

00:16:28.910 --> 00:16:33.110 align:middle line:84%
So if you have an
ordered set, and A here

00:16:33.110 --> 00:16:40.400 align:middle line:84%
is a subset of S that
is bounded from above--

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:47.230 align:middle line:90%


00:16:47.230 --> 00:16:55.530 align:middle line:84%
from above-- then, it is
complete if S is complete.

00:16:55.530 --> 00:17:03.630 align:middle line:84%
So if S is complete,
then any subset

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:11.829 align:middle line:84%
that is bounded from above
has a least upper bound.

00:17:11.829 --> 00:17:18.840 align:middle line:90%
Then A has a least upper bound.

00:17:18.840 --> 00:17:24.069 align:middle line:90%


00:17:24.069 --> 00:17:31.050 align:middle line:84%
And that least upper bound is
denoted by the sup of A, right?

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:36.180 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here,
it has the property

00:17:36.180 --> 00:17:48.340 align:middle line:84%
that a is less than or equal
to M for all a in A. And also,

00:17:48.340 --> 00:17:54.430 align:middle line:90%
if M1 is another upper bound--

00:17:54.430 --> 00:17:57.060 align:middle line:90%


00:17:57.060 --> 00:18:03.820 align:middle line:90%
upper bound for A--

00:18:03.820 --> 00:18:08.560 align:middle line:84%
then M is less than
or equal to M1.

00:18:08.560 --> 00:18:11.300 align:middle line:90%


00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:15.020 align:middle line:90%
So that's a least upper bound.

00:18:15.020 --> 00:18:17.820 align:middle line:90%
And the same thing is--

00:18:17.820 --> 00:18:22.860 align:middle line:84%
so, similarly, when we
have an ordered set,

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:26.770 align:middle line:84%
and we have a set, if it's
complete, and if we have--

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:33.140 align:middle line:90%


00:18:33.140 --> 00:18:56.460 align:middle line:84%
if A here is bounded
from below, then inf of A

00:18:56.460 --> 00:19:06.460 align:middle line:84%
is the least upper-- is
the largest, the greatest,

00:19:06.460 --> 00:19:14.400 align:middle line:90%
lower bound for A.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:19.020 align:middle line:84%
So this, again, means that
this number here, little m--

00:19:19.020 --> 00:19:28.620 align:middle line:84%
so m here is less or
equal to a for all a in A.

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:42.820 align:middle line:84%
And if m1 here is
another lower bound,

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:48.940 align:middle line:84%
then m1 here is
less or equal to m.

00:19:48.940 --> 00:19:51.780 align:middle line:90%
So this is a symmetric property.

00:19:51.780 --> 00:19:56.860 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, R, the
reals, is complete.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:01.440 align:middle line:84%
So whenever you take a
bounded subset of the real--

00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:04.180 align:middle line:84%
so if it's bounded, that means
that it's bounded from above

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:05.660 align:middle line:90%
and below--

00:20:05.660 --> 00:20:09.880 align:middle line:84%
then it has a least upper bound
and a greatest lower bound.

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:15.220 align:middle line:84%
And those are denoted
by sup and inf.

00:20:15.220 --> 00:20:19.620 align:middle line:84%
And in general,
sup and inf are not

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:24.660 align:middle line:84%
in the set itself, in the
set A. I mean, they could be.

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:27.627 align:middle line:84%
But in general,
they wouldn't be.

00:20:27.627 --> 00:20:29.710 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The example that
we talked about earlier

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:32.860 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] open set
[INAUDIBLE] but that

00:20:32.860 --> 00:20:34.610 align:middle line:90%
is not complete [INAUDIBLE].

00:20:34.610 --> 00:20:36.170 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: That's right.

00:20:36.170 --> 00:20:38.430 align:middle line:90%
So no.

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:42.666 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking
at this set here,

00:20:42.666 --> 00:20:56.490 align:middle line:84%
so suppose that this
here is the set S.

00:20:56.490 --> 00:21:01.610 align:middle line:84%
And if you take A
here is a subset of S,

00:21:01.610 --> 00:21:06.250 align:middle line:84%
and A here is bounded
from-- let's say that A here

00:21:06.250 --> 00:21:07.580 align:middle line:90%
is bounded from below.

00:21:07.580 --> 00:21:16.010 align:middle line:90%


00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:20.930 align:middle line:84%
If it's bounded from below,
then it couldn't be--

00:21:20.930 --> 00:21:26.530 align:middle line:84%
this set here, this here
is not bounded from below.

00:21:26.530 --> 00:21:29.770 align:middle line:84%
So it means that if
it's bounded from below,

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:35.970 align:middle line:84%
then A here could not have
numbers that was approaching 0.

00:21:35.970 --> 00:21:39.930 align:middle line:84%
And so actually, if it
is bounded from below,

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:42.890 align:middle line:84%
if it's a subset of this,
and it's bounded from below,

00:21:42.890 --> 00:21:45.850 align:middle line:84%
then actually, it would
have a least lower bound--

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:47.590 align:middle line:90%
a greatest lower bound, right?

00:21:47.590 --> 00:21:49.370 align:middle line:90%
It should mean--

00:21:49.370 --> 00:21:51.130 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:21:51.130 --> 00:21:52.190 align:middle line:90%
So it is--

00:21:52.190 --> 00:21:53.970 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'm not going
to prove anything

00:21:53.970 --> 00:21:55.810 align:middle line:90%
is complete or not complete.

00:21:55.810 --> 00:22:07.330 align:middle line:84%
But it's pretty convincing
that it is actually complete,

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:08.010 align:middle line:90%
in this sense.

00:22:08.010 --> 00:22:10.150 align:middle line:84%
There's another sense
that is not complete.

00:22:10.150 --> 00:22:12.610 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, in this
sense, it is complete.

00:22:12.610 --> 00:22:13.130 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:22:13.130 --> 00:22:15.730 align:middle line:90%
No, it's a little bit--

00:22:15.730 --> 00:22:17.250 align:middle line:90%
it can be confusing.

00:22:17.250 --> 00:22:19.730 align:middle line:84%
Later on, we'll talk about
maybe some other notion

00:22:19.730 --> 00:22:20.670 align:middle line:90%
of completeness.

00:22:20.670 --> 00:22:21.910 align:middle line:90%
And then it's not complete.

00:22:21.910 --> 00:22:27.090 align:middle line:84%
But in this notion,
it is complete.

00:22:27.090 --> 00:22:33.090 align:middle line:84%
OK, so the next thing
I want to get to

00:22:33.090 --> 00:22:35.910 align:middle line:84%
is this with how to write
a mathematical proof.

00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:39.138 align:middle line:90%


00:22:39.138 --> 00:22:44.570 align:middle line:84%
And again, that's a
super important thing

00:22:44.570 --> 00:22:48.630 align:middle line:90%
to learn in this class.

00:22:48.630 --> 00:22:52.850 align:middle line:90%
And it's not just a--

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:59.610 align:middle line:90%
it's not just a formal thing.

00:22:59.610 --> 00:23:01.550 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's-- yeah.

00:23:01.550 --> 00:23:03.690 align:middle line:90%
It may seem like a formal thing.

00:23:03.690 --> 00:23:07.210 align:middle line:90%
Why bother with that?

00:23:07.210 --> 00:23:09.970 align:middle line:90%
But it's really, really useful.

00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:16.850 align:middle line:84%
And the more complicated things
become, the more useful it is.

00:23:16.850 --> 00:23:21.290 align:middle line:84%
And so I want to
illustrate this with how

00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:23.200 align:middle line:90%
to write a mathematical proof.

00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:25.420 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
illustrate this--

00:23:25.420 --> 00:23:38.420 align:middle line:84%
so we will illustrate
it by proving again--

00:23:38.420 --> 00:23:41.110 align:middle line:90%


00:23:41.110 --> 00:23:58.840 align:middle line:84%
by writing a formal proof
of why square root of 2

00:23:58.840 --> 00:23:59.750 align:middle line:90%
is a real number.

00:23:59.750 --> 00:24:02.320 align:middle line:90%


00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:04.880 align:middle line:90%
So I want to write--

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:09.440 align:middle line:84%
so last time, we talked
about that square root of 2

00:24:09.440 --> 00:24:12.120 align:middle line:90%
was a real number.

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:14.840 align:middle line:84%
But when we proved
it, it was more

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:18.360 align:middle line:90%
like we talked about the idea.

00:24:18.360 --> 00:24:21.500 align:middle line:84%
And so then the
question is-- so if you

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:24.440 align:middle line:84%
have-- imagine you have
a piece of scrap paper.

00:24:24.440 --> 00:24:27.000 align:middle line:84%
What we did last time
was what you would

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.500 align:middle line:90%
be writing on the scrap paper.

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:33.360 align:middle line:84%
So I want to talk about, if you
were handing it in or showing it

00:24:33.360 --> 00:24:37.920 align:middle line:84%
to somebody, then
you wouldn't do that.

00:24:37.920 --> 00:24:40.160 align:middle line:90%
You would do what we do now.

00:24:40.160 --> 00:24:44.280 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't necessarily make
for a great-- a formal proof

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:47.200 align:middle line:84%
doesn't necessarily make
for a great lecture,

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:48.810 align:middle line:90%
because it's kind of formal.

00:24:48.810 --> 00:24:52.424 align:middle line:90%


00:24:52.424 --> 00:24:58.120 align:middle line:84%
So let me try to explain
how you should write this.

00:24:58.120 --> 00:25:02.040 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is a
very simple example.

00:25:02.040 --> 00:25:07.420 align:middle line:84%
But hopefully, it will give
you an idea of what to do.

00:25:07.420 --> 00:25:11.320 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is a really
important part of this class

00:25:11.320 --> 00:25:18.560 align:middle line:84%
that you're bound to use in
many other classes later on.

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:22.600 align:middle line:84%
OK, so let's first talk about
what was square root of 2.

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:24.960 align:middle line:90%
So square root of 2--

00:25:24.960 --> 00:25:27.240 align:middle line:90%
this here was a number.

00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:32.720 align:middle line:84%
And it was given by that it has
a property-- that it's positive,

00:25:32.720 --> 00:25:37.140 align:middle line:84%
and when you square
it, then you get 2.

00:25:37.140 --> 00:25:39.120 align:middle line:84%
That was what square
root of 2 was.

00:25:39.120 --> 00:25:41.840 align:middle line:90%


00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:51.480 align:middle line:84%
Now, so we again-- so we want to
prove-- so this is the theorem.

00:25:51.480 --> 00:26:00.640 align:middle line:84%
So theorem-- square root
of 2 is a real number.

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:03.680 align:middle line:84%
So I know-- maybe I should
write it more formally.

00:26:03.680 --> 00:26:14.215 align:middle line:84%
There exists alpha
greater than 0--

00:26:14.215 --> 00:26:22.950 align:middle line:84%
this is alpha in R with alpha
greater than 0 and alpha

00:26:22.950 --> 00:26:24.730 align:middle line:90%
squared is equal to 2.

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:29.350 align:middle line:90%


00:26:29.350 --> 00:26:41.590 align:middle line:84%
Now, we look at the set A.
The set A is the numbers--

00:26:41.590 --> 00:26:51.830 align:middle line:84%
it's the x, such
that x is positive,

00:26:51.830 --> 00:27:00.645 align:middle line:84%
and x squared is less
than or equal to 2.

00:27:00.645 --> 00:27:03.355 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] see
what x is, like where--

00:27:03.355 --> 00:27:04.230 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:27:04.230 --> 00:27:10.430 align:middle line:84%
So x here-- so now I will
specialize to the real numbers.

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:12.250 align:middle line:84%
So that was why I didn't
actually write it.

00:27:12.250 --> 00:27:13.950 align:middle line:90%
But you're right.

00:27:13.950 --> 00:27:15.520 align:middle line:90%
It certainly can't hurt.

00:27:15.520 --> 00:27:17.590 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that's the theorem.

00:27:17.590 --> 00:27:19.720 align:middle line:84%
And so now we try to
write a formal proof.

00:27:19.720 --> 00:27:26.030 align:middle line:90%


00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:43.150 align:middle line:84%
Observe first that
A here is nonempty,

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:47.670 align:middle line:90%
since 1 is in A, right?

00:27:47.670 --> 00:27:49.470 align:middle line:90%
1 is positive.

00:27:49.470 --> 00:27:52.370 align:middle line:84%
And when you square
1, you get 1.

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:54.670 align:middle line:84%
So this is definitely
less than or equal to 2.

00:27:54.670 --> 00:27:56.480 align:middle line:90%
So A here is nonempty.

00:27:56.480 --> 00:27:59.910 align:middle line:90%


00:27:59.910 --> 00:28:14.870 align:middle line:84%
Next, observe that
A here is bounded--

00:28:14.870 --> 00:28:15.860 align:middle line:90%
is bounded from above.

00:28:15.860 --> 00:28:21.870 align:middle line:90%


00:28:21.870 --> 00:28:25.350 align:middle line:84%
In general, by the way,
when you write a proof,

00:28:25.350 --> 00:28:28.950 align:middle line:84%
then you really only try
to establish the properties

00:28:28.950 --> 00:28:31.810 align:middle line:84%
that you need, because
otherwise, it's confusing.

00:28:31.810 --> 00:28:33.950 align:middle line:84%
If you establish all
kinds of other properties

00:28:33.950 --> 00:28:37.390 align:middle line:84%
that is not needed, that
just makes it confusing.

00:28:37.390 --> 00:28:39.180 align:middle line:90%
So it's bounded from above.

00:28:39.180 --> 00:28:41.870 align:middle line:90%


00:28:41.870 --> 00:28:43.010 align:middle line:90%
And this is just because--

00:28:43.010 --> 00:28:48.590 align:middle line:90%


00:28:48.590 --> 00:29:05.662 align:middle line:90%
since 2 is an upper bound for A.

00:29:05.662 --> 00:29:08.070 align:middle line:84%
Now, the next thing
is-- so now we have

00:29:08.070 --> 00:29:10.730 align:middle line:90%
a non-empty bounded subset.

00:29:10.730 --> 00:29:18.700 align:middle line:84%
So we set-- so set alpha
equal to the sup of a.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:21.020 align:middle line:90%
And we want to prove--

00:29:21.020 --> 00:29:31.420 align:middle line:84%
want to show that alpha is
positive, and alpha squared

00:29:31.420 --> 00:29:32.480 align:middle line:90%
is equal to 2.

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:39.380 align:middle line:90%


00:29:39.380 --> 00:29:49.960 align:middle line:90%
Well-- all right.

00:29:49.960 --> 00:29:51.840 align:middle line:84%
By definition, the
way we defined--

00:29:51.840 --> 00:29:55.100 align:middle line:90%


00:29:55.100 --> 00:30:01.020 align:middle line:84%
the way we defined A, all the
elements in A were positive.

00:30:01.020 --> 00:30:12.090 align:middle line:84%
So by definition,
0 is a lower bound.

00:30:12.090 --> 00:30:17.060 align:middle line:90%


00:30:17.060 --> 00:30:22.100 align:middle line:84%
So you for sure have that 0
here is less or equal to--

00:30:22.100 --> 00:30:26.100 align:middle line:84%
well, it's actually-- I mean,
even 1 is a lower bound.

00:30:26.100 --> 00:30:31.300 align:middle line:84%
So you can also just say that
since 1 is a lower bound--

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:37.340 align:middle line:84%
since 1 here is in A, you
also have that this alpha here

00:30:37.340 --> 00:30:41.940 align:middle line:84%
must be bigger or
equal to 1, because it

00:30:41.940 --> 00:30:46.940 align:middle line:84%
was supposed to be an upper
bound for A, so in particular.

00:30:46.940 --> 00:30:55.220 align:middle line:84%
Now-- and so we have that
alpha is less than 1.

00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:57.440 align:middle line:90%
And it's the least upper bound.

00:30:57.440 --> 00:30:59.040 align:middle line:90%
And 2 was an upper bound.

00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:02.980 align:middle line:90%
So you have this, since--

00:31:02.980 --> 00:31:07.820 align:middle line:84%
maybe I should write
it with this thing.

00:31:07.820 --> 00:31:14.780 align:middle line:84%
Since 1 is in A, we
have that 1 here,

00:31:14.780 --> 00:31:15.950 align:middle line:90%
less than or equal to alpha.

00:31:15.950 --> 00:31:19.700 align:middle line:90%


00:31:19.700 --> 00:31:35.900 align:middle line:84%
And since alpha is
the least upper bound,

00:31:35.900 --> 00:31:49.140 align:middle line:84%
and 2 is an upper bound,
we have that alpha

00:31:49.140 --> 00:31:50.480 align:middle line:90%
is less than or equal to 2.

00:31:50.480 --> 00:31:53.020 align:middle line:90%


00:31:53.020 --> 00:31:55.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, remember, we were
going to do it exactly

00:31:55.580 --> 00:31:56.840 align:middle line:90%
like we did last time.

00:31:56.840 --> 00:32:01.860 align:middle line:84%
But we're just going to write it
down in a proper way as a proof.

00:32:01.860 --> 00:32:04.820 align:middle line:84%
So remember that last time,
we then divided the proof

00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:08.300 align:middle line:90%
into two steps.

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:10.620 align:middle line:90%
The first step was--

00:32:10.620 --> 00:32:15.900 align:middle line:84%
so part 1-- so now, so all
we need to prove-- maybe

00:32:15.900 --> 00:32:17.140 align:middle line:90%
I'll just say that.

00:32:17.140 --> 00:32:26.980 align:middle line:84%
All we need to
prove, to show, is

00:32:26.980 --> 00:32:31.020 align:middle line:84%
that alpha squared
is equal to 2,

00:32:31.020 --> 00:32:33.100 align:middle line:84%
because we already have
it as positive now,

00:32:33.100 --> 00:32:36.016 align:middle line:90%
because it's bigger than 1.

00:32:36.016 --> 00:32:40.260 align:middle line:84%
And so there was two parts
to this, step 1 and step 2,

00:32:40.260 --> 00:32:43.140 align:middle line:90%
or part 1 and part 2.

00:32:43.140 --> 00:32:46.180 align:middle line:84%
The first part
was-- so part 1, we

00:32:46.180 --> 00:33:00.930 align:middle line:84%
will show that alpha squared
is less than or equal to 2.

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:07.106 align:middle line:90%


00:33:07.106 --> 00:33:09.510 align:middle line:90%
And so we prove this--

00:33:09.510 --> 00:33:13.320 align:middle line:90%
so assume not.

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:19.250 align:middle line:90%


00:33:19.250 --> 00:33:20.770 align:middle line:90%
We will show that that leads--

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:29.955 align:middle line:90%


00:33:29.955 --> 00:33:50.290 align:middle line:84%
that this leads to a
contradiction to that alpha

00:33:50.290 --> 00:34:03.270 align:middle line:90%
is the least upper bound for A.

00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:07.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm writing everything out
here, just to illustrate it.

00:34:07.310 --> 00:34:11.170 align:middle line:84%
As you get more and
more familiar with this,

00:34:11.170 --> 00:34:13.370 align:middle line:90%
then the structure is the same.

00:34:13.370 --> 00:34:16.949 align:middle line:84%
But some of these steps will
seem almost too trivial.

00:34:16.949 --> 00:34:18.610 align:middle line:90%
And that's probably fine.

00:34:18.610 --> 00:34:21.850 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it's
always good to err on more

00:34:21.850 --> 00:34:23.759 align:middle line:90%
details than fewer details.

00:34:23.759 --> 00:34:27.596 align:middle line:90%


00:34:27.596 --> 00:34:29.929 align:middle line:90%
So this is what we want to do.

00:34:29.929 --> 00:34:35.730 align:middle line:90%
So we assume not.

00:34:35.730 --> 00:34:44.050 align:middle line:84%
So assume that alpha squared
is strictly bigger than 2.

00:34:44.050 --> 00:34:47.330 align:middle line:90%


00:34:47.330 --> 00:34:50.409 align:middle line:84%
Then-- and this is
where it deviates more

00:34:50.409 --> 00:34:54.090 align:middle line:90%
from how we did it last time.

00:34:54.090 --> 00:34:56.090 align:middle line:84%
And that's why what
we did last time

00:34:56.090 --> 00:35:02.970 align:middle line:84%
is really what you want to
have on the scrap paper.

00:35:02.970 --> 00:35:06.770 align:middle line:84%
What we did last time
was like the idea.

00:35:06.770 --> 00:35:10.090 align:middle line:84%
And then, once you
see the idea, then

00:35:10.090 --> 00:35:16.450 align:middle line:84%
you try to write it as a formal
proof, like what we do now.

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:21.530 align:middle line:90%
And so, so assume not.

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:25.410 align:middle line:90%
Set h equal to--

00:35:25.410 --> 00:35:30.930 align:middle line:84%
so I'm going to set h equal
to alpha squared minus 2

00:35:30.930 --> 00:35:32.760 align:middle line:90%
over 4 alpha.

00:35:32.760 --> 00:35:35.530 align:middle line:90%


00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:39.010 align:middle line:84%
Obviously, if this was the
first time you would do it,

00:35:39.010 --> 00:35:41.910 align:middle line:84%
you wouldn't just come up with
this sort of thing, right?

00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:45.090 align:middle line:84%
This is coming from the
scrap paper that you had.

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:47.610 align:middle line:84%
So you're setting
h equal to that.

00:35:47.610 --> 00:35:48.740 align:middle line:90%
And then you observe--

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:51.970 align:middle line:90%


00:35:51.970 --> 00:36:04.000 align:middle line:84%
you observe that since alpha
here is bigger than 1, and alpha

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:09.920 align:middle line:84%
squared is bigger
than 2, since that,

00:36:09.920 --> 00:36:13.600 align:middle line:84%
then the nominator
here is positive.

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:15.800 align:middle line:90%
And the denominator is positive.

00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:17.960 align:middle line:90%
So h here is positive.

00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:21.280 align:middle line:90%


00:36:21.280 --> 00:36:23.420 align:middle line:90%
You also have that--

00:36:23.420 --> 00:36:25.670 align:middle line:90%
you also have that h is--

00:36:25.670 --> 00:36:30.460 align:middle line:90%


00:36:30.460 --> 00:36:30.960 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:36.680 align:middle line:84%
You also have
automatically that h is--

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:37.780 align:middle line:90%
maybe we don't need that.

00:36:37.780 --> 00:36:38.940 align:middle line:90%
Let's see if we need that.

00:36:38.940 --> 00:36:42.120 align:middle line:90%
So OK.

00:36:42.120 --> 00:36:55.520 align:middle line:84%
So now you set alpha 1
equal to alpha minus h.

00:36:55.520 --> 00:37:10.300 align:middle line:84%
And what I want to prove is-- so
we want to show that alpha here,

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:21.520 align:middle line:84%
alpha 1, is an
upper bound for A.

00:37:21.520 --> 00:37:25.160 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove that this
is an upper bound for A.

00:37:25.160 --> 00:37:28.840 align:middle line:84%
The first thing I want to do--
if it's an upper bound, it does

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:30.620 align:middle line:90%
need to be positive.

00:37:30.620 --> 00:37:31.630 align:middle line:90%
So let's check that.

00:37:31.630 --> 00:37:40.120 align:middle line:90%


00:37:40.120 --> 00:37:46.360 align:middle line:84%
So since we already have
that h was positive--

00:37:46.360 --> 00:37:51.440 align:middle line:84%
so this here was h was
positive, alpha squared minus 2

00:37:51.440 --> 00:37:53.800 align:middle line:90%
over 4 alpha.

00:37:53.800 --> 00:37:57.360 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is
less or equal to--

00:37:57.360 --> 00:37:59.020 align:middle line:90%
I can even forget about the 2.

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:02.760 align:middle line:84%
So I can write it as alpha
squared over 4 alpha.

00:38:02.760 --> 00:38:04.360 align:middle line:90%
And so this here is--

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:06.400 align:middle line:90%
I can just divide by alpha.

00:38:06.400 --> 00:38:09.080 align:middle line:90%
So I get alpha over 4.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:14.200 align:middle line:84%
So I have-- since we have that h
here is less than alpha over 4,

00:38:14.200 --> 00:38:22.020 align:middle line:90%
then alpha 1 is bigger than--

00:38:22.020 --> 00:38:30.208 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal
to 3/4 of alpha,

00:38:30.208 --> 00:38:34.400 align:middle line:84%
because I'm subtracting
at most alpha over 4.

00:38:34.400 --> 00:38:37.840 align:middle line:84%
And so there's still 3/4
of alpha left, right?

00:38:37.840 --> 00:38:40.920 align:middle line:84%
So I have this-- in
particular, this thing here.

00:38:40.920 --> 00:38:43.720 align:middle line:84%
It's actually bigger
than 3 over 4.

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:45.380 align:middle line:84%
But I just need
it to be positive.

00:38:45.380 --> 00:38:49.640 align:middle line:90%


00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:51.240 align:middle line:90%
So that's positive.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:58.670 align:middle line:84%
So alpha over--
alpha 1 is positive.

00:38:58.670 --> 00:39:04.990 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm looking at
alpha 1 squared, right?

00:39:04.990 --> 00:39:13.260 align:middle line:84%
And so alpha 1 squared is
equal to alpha minus h squared.

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:15.950 align:middle line:90%


00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:21.950 align:middle line:84%
So this here is equal
to alpha squared plus h

00:39:21.950 --> 00:39:24.930 align:middle line:90%
squared minus 2 alpha h.

00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:28.940 align:middle line:90%


00:39:28.940 --> 00:39:36.830 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is less
or equal to alpha squared.

00:39:36.830 --> 00:39:40.470 align:middle line:90%
Here, h here is--

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:47.950 align:middle line:84%
h is-- so now I'd like to say
that h is less or equal to 1.

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:51.030 align:middle line:84%
Actually, I'm going to use
that it's less than 1/2.

00:39:51.030 --> 00:39:52.890 align:middle line:90%
And why is that the case?

00:39:52.890 --> 00:39:56.330 align:middle line:90%
It's actually, alpha itself--

00:39:56.330 --> 00:39:59.430 align:middle line:84%
we already know that
alpha was less than 2.

00:39:59.430 --> 00:40:06.310 align:middle line:84%
So you have that this thing here
is less or equal to 2 over 4.

00:40:06.310 --> 00:40:09.290 align:middle line:90%
So this is equal to 1/2, right?

00:40:09.290 --> 00:40:14.830 align:middle line:90%


00:40:14.830 --> 00:40:20.230 align:middle line:90%
So now I have that--

00:40:20.230 --> 00:40:27.750 align:middle line:84%
now I have that this thing
here is less than plus--

00:40:27.750 --> 00:40:30.510 align:middle line:90%


00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:36.250 align:middle line:84%
here, I just use that it's
less than this thing here.

00:40:36.250 --> 00:40:37.190 align:middle line:90%
This here, I just--

00:40:37.190 --> 00:40:40.850 align:middle line:84%
I think it's fine
to just use h here.

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:42.130 align:middle line:90%
I could use h over 2.

00:40:42.130 --> 00:40:43.450 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I'll use h over 2.

00:40:43.450 --> 00:40:46.190 align:middle line:84%
So one of the h, I
just replaced by 1/2.

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:47.710 align:middle line:90%
That is an upper bound.

00:40:47.710 --> 00:40:52.710 align:middle line:84%
And the other one,
I just keep, right?

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:57.990 align:middle line:84%
So I have that and
then minus 2 alpha h.

00:40:57.990 --> 00:41:03.510 align:middle line:84%
But if you multiply
alpha by h, then it's

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.830 align:middle line:90%
disappeared in the denominator.

00:41:05.830 --> 00:41:09.630 align:middle line:90%
So you're getting minus 2.

00:41:09.630 --> 00:41:18.500 align:middle line:84%
And then you're getting
alpha squared minus 2 over 4.

00:41:18.500 --> 00:41:22.510 align:middle line:90%


00:41:22.510 --> 00:41:25.630 align:middle line:90%
And so here, you get--

00:41:25.630 --> 00:41:30.870 align:middle line:84%
this here becomes
alpha squared plus--

00:41:30.870 --> 00:41:32.950 align:middle line:90%
and here, I'm just writing in.

00:41:32.950 --> 00:41:34.430 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's--
at the moment,

00:41:34.430 --> 00:41:37.510 align:middle line:90%
we're overkilling it here.

00:41:37.510 --> 00:41:40.750 align:middle line:84%
And so I can replace
this one here.

00:41:40.750 --> 00:41:43.750 align:middle line:90%
So let me just write it in--

00:41:43.750 --> 00:41:51.440 align:middle line:84%
alpha squared minus 2 over
2 times 4 times alpha.

00:41:51.440 --> 00:41:59.000 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is alpha
squared minus 2 over 2.

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:01.420 align:middle line:84%
This 2 cancels with
one of those 2.

00:42:01.420 --> 00:42:02.720 align:middle line:90%
So this is what I have.

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:06.180 align:middle line:90%


00:42:06.180 --> 00:42:14.900 align:middle line:84%
And so now I get that
this thing here is--

00:42:14.900 --> 00:42:17.330 align:middle line:84%
so I get that this
thing here is--

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:24.980 align:middle line:90%


00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:26.440 align:middle line:90%
we're adding it here.

00:42:26.440 --> 00:42:31.500 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is alpha squared.

00:42:31.500 --> 00:42:35.820 align:middle line:84%
So let me just bring
these two together.

00:42:35.820 --> 00:42:39.680 align:middle line:84%
Let me just-- maybe I'll
just combine all of these.

00:42:39.680 --> 00:42:42.330 align:middle line:84%
I don't think I
need it this well.

00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:48.216 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.216 --> 00:42:48.716 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:42:48.716 --> 00:42:52.620 align:middle line:84%
So if I combine
these two here, I

00:42:52.620 --> 00:42:56.920 align:middle line:84%
think I'm fine with
just having a 2 here--

00:42:56.920 --> 00:43:00.300 align:middle line:90%
a 4, sorry, instead of the 2.

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:07.660 align:middle line:84%
So if I do that, then
I get alpha squared.

00:43:07.660 --> 00:43:10.040 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I should just bring it
on the common denominator.

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:13.340 align:middle line:84%
So this here, this alpha,
sorry, I'm getting rid of.

00:43:13.340 --> 00:43:18.180 align:middle line:84%
I'm replacing-- I'm bounding
this from above by alpha squared

00:43:18.180 --> 00:43:20.300 align:middle line:90%
plus--

00:43:20.300 --> 00:43:23.120 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to just
make it easier for myself.

00:43:23.120 --> 00:43:27.160 align:middle line:84%
I think it's fine to just use
that alpha is bounded by 1.

00:43:27.160 --> 00:43:32.930 align:middle line:84%
And then you can just bound it
by alpha squared minus 2 over 4.

00:43:32.930 --> 00:43:35.660 align:middle line:90%


00:43:35.660 --> 00:43:49.740 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is alpha
squared minus 2 over 2, right?

00:43:49.740 --> 00:43:54.820 align:middle line:84%
Here, again, I'm just using that
alpha was bigger or equal to 1,

00:43:54.820 --> 00:43:57.060 align:middle line:90%
and--

00:43:57.060 --> 00:43:58.386 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:43:58.386 --> 00:44:02.420 align:middle line:84%
And then I just actually
ignore this 2, right?

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:04.600 align:middle line:84%
So this is definitely
an upper bound.

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:07.380 align:middle line:90%


00:44:07.380 --> 00:44:09.980 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see
that this thing here

00:44:09.980 --> 00:44:13.780 align:middle line:90%
is equal to alpha squared.

00:44:13.780 --> 00:44:16.400 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, you can
think about this thing here--

00:44:16.400 --> 00:44:19.580 align:middle line:84%
you can write this thing here,
if you will, as alpha squared,

00:44:19.580 --> 00:44:26.700 align:middle line:84%
plus alpha squared minus 2
over 4, minus 2 alpha squared,

00:44:26.700 --> 00:44:32.020 align:middle line:90%
minus 2 over 4.

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:36.020 align:middle line:84%
And so what you get is
that it's alpha squared,

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:40.440 align:middle line:84%
minus alpha squared,
minus 2 over 4.

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:43.020 align:middle line:90%


00:44:43.020 --> 00:44:46.570 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is
now-- this thing here

00:44:46.570 --> 00:44:50.010 align:middle line:84%
is positive, because alpha
squared was strictly bigger

00:44:50.010 --> 00:44:50.890 align:middle line:90%
than 2.

00:44:50.890 --> 00:44:52.310 align:middle line:90%
This is positive.

00:44:52.310 --> 00:44:54.350 align:middle line:84%
So this is strictly
less than alpha squared.

00:44:54.350 --> 00:44:57.170 align:middle line:90%


00:44:57.170 --> 00:44:59.410 align:middle line:90%
And so this here would also--

00:44:59.410 --> 00:45:07.820 align:middle line:84%
which is still-- so this thing
here is also an upper bound.

00:45:07.820 --> 00:45:09.850 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry.

00:45:09.850 --> 00:45:12.450 align:middle line:90%
I need to-- no, sorry.

00:45:12.450 --> 00:45:12.950 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:12.950 --> 00:45:13.680 align:middle line:90%
So I have this.

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:21.850 align:middle line:90%


00:45:21.850 --> 00:45:24.970 align:middle line:90%
No, no, sorry about that.

00:45:24.970 --> 00:45:27.730 align:middle line:90%
OK, so-- yeah, no, I-- sorry.

00:45:27.730 --> 00:45:31.650 align:middle line:90%


00:45:31.650 --> 00:45:33.750 align:middle line:84%
OK, let's just go
over this again.

00:45:33.750 --> 00:45:34.250 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:45:34.250 --> 00:45:38.050 align:middle line:90%


00:45:38.050 --> 00:45:39.950 align:middle line:84%
So what am I trying
to prove here?

00:45:39.950 --> 00:45:42.110 align:middle line:84%
I'm trying to write
down the formal--

00:45:42.110 --> 00:45:46.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's the problem, that
it got so formal that I was now

00:45:46.770 --> 00:45:52.010 align:middle line:84%
in-- so what I'm trying to prove
here is that I want to say--

00:45:52.010 --> 00:45:58.850 align:middle line:84%
this part 1 is that alpha
squared is less or equal to 1.

00:45:58.850 --> 00:46:01.730 align:middle line:84%
This is what--
less or equal to 2.

00:46:01.730 --> 00:46:03.970 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to prove.

00:46:03.970 --> 00:46:05.870 align:middle line:90%
This is part 1.

00:46:05.870 --> 00:46:07.470 align:middle line:90%
And so I assume not.

00:46:07.470 --> 00:46:13.130 align:middle line:84%
So I assume that alpha squared
was strictly bigger than 2.

00:46:13.130 --> 00:46:18.770 align:middle line:84%
If alpha squared was strictly
bigger than 2, here, you have 0.

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:20.770 align:middle line:90%
Here, you have alpha.

00:46:20.770 --> 00:46:24.650 align:middle line:90%
And now we define this alpha 0.

00:46:24.650 --> 00:46:29.730 align:middle line:84%
Alpha 0 was to the left,
so to speak, of alpha,

00:46:29.730 --> 00:46:33.490 align:middle line:84%
because it was
subtracting a little bit.

00:46:33.490 --> 00:46:37.370 align:middle line:84%
And what I want to show
is that this alpha 0--

00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:41.270 align:middle line:84%
I want to show that this alpha
0 is also an upper bound.

00:46:41.270 --> 00:46:44.010 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove
that this square here

00:46:44.010 --> 00:46:46.190 align:middle line:90%
is also bigger than 2.

00:46:46.190 --> 00:46:49.343 align:middle line:90%
That's what I want to prove.

00:46:49.343 --> 00:46:51.290 align:middle line:90%
So I want to find--

00:46:51.290 --> 00:46:54.670 align:middle line:90%
I want to find a lower bound.

00:46:54.670 --> 00:46:56.850 align:middle line:84%
And that lower bound
should be true.

00:46:56.850 --> 00:47:00.736 align:middle line:84%
So this is not exactly
what I wanted to do.

00:47:00.736 --> 00:47:03.010 align:middle line:84%
So let's just go
through it here.

00:47:03.010 --> 00:47:03.810 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:47:03.810 --> 00:47:05.390 align:middle line:90%
So this here was correct.

00:47:05.390 --> 00:47:07.700 align:middle line:84%
And this here is really
for the second part.

00:47:07.700 --> 00:47:11.770 align:middle line:90%


00:47:11.770 --> 00:47:13.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:13.970 --> 00:47:17.290 align:middle line:90%
So we define it like this.

00:47:17.290 --> 00:47:25.090 align:middle line:84%
And now I say that this thing
here is bigger or equal to--

00:47:25.090 --> 00:47:27.570 align:middle line:90%
I want to bound it from below.

00:47:27.570 --> 00:47:30.430 align:middle line:84%
And so then I can
ignore the h squared.

00:47:30.430 --> 00:47:33.070 align:middle line:84%
So it's bigger than--
because that's positive.

00:47:33.070 --> 00:47:36.590 align:middle line:84%
So it's bigger than alpha
squared minus 2 alpha h.

00:47:36.590 --> 00:47:39.340 align:middle line:90%


00:47:39.340 --> 00:47:41.620 align:middle line:90%
And this thing here is--

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:46.660 align:middle line:84%
so this is equal to alpha
squared minus 2 alpha.

00:47:46.660 --> 00:47:49.000 align:middle line:90%
I fill in what h was.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:50.170 align:middle line:90%
This here was h.

00:47:50.170 --> 00:47:56.239 align:middle line:90%


00:47:56.239 --> 00:48:00.880 align:middle line:84%
And then you see that this
here cancels with that.

00:48:00.880 --> 00:48:04.020 align:middle line:84%
And this here-- and
you're getting that--

00:48:04.020 --> 00:48:05.310 align:middle line:90%
you're getting alpha squared--

00:48:05.310 --> 00:48:07.850 align:middle line:90%


00:48:07.850 --> 00:48:18.720 align:middle line:84%
this is this alpha squared minus
alpha squared minus 2 over 2.

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:21.840 align:middle line:84%
And this thing
here is equal to--

00:48:21.840 --> 00:48:26.400 align:middle line:84%
this is equal to
alpha squared over 2.

00:48:26.400 --> 00:48:28.520 align:middle line:90%
This is subtracting that.

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:30.700 align:middle line:90%
And then you're adding, right?

00:48:30.700 --> 00:48:32.440 align:middle line:90%
You're adding 1.

00:48:32.440 --> 00:48:35.225 align:middle line:90%
So this is what it is.

00:48:35.225 --> 00:48:38.280 align:middle line:84%
Alpha-- we have already
proven that alpha

00:48:38.280 --> 00:48:41.120 align:middle line:90%
here was bigger or equal to 1.

00:48:41.120 --> 00:48:45.360 align:middle line:84%
So using-- so this here
is bigger or equal to--

00:48:45.360 --> 00:48:48.840 align:middle line:84%
I claim that this here
is bigger or equal to 2

00:48:48.840 --> 00:48:57.220 align:middle line:84%
using that alpha is
bigger or equal to 1.

00:48:57.220 --> 00:48:59.824 align:middle line:90%


00:48:59.824 --> 00:49:03.360 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that alpha 1, that

00:49:03.360 --> 00:49:06.280 align:middle line:84%
is a smaller number,
because you're subtracting

00:49:06.280 --> 00:49:09.280 align:middle line:90%
a positive number from alpha.

00:49:09.280 --> 00:49:12.480 align:middle line:90%
That is also an upper bound.

00:49:12.480 --> 00:49:16.200 align:middle line:84%
So this is contradicting--
so this contradicts.

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:18.920 align:middle line:90%
And then one often writes--

00:49:18.920 --> 00:49:21.880 align:middle line:84%
one often writes
this symbol here.

00:49:21.880 --> 00:49:26.720 align:middle line:84%
This is a standard symbol that
means this is a contradiction.

00:49:26.720 --> 00:49:27.460 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:29.600 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Did you
say using that alpha

00:49:29.600 --> 00:49:31.600 align:middle line:90%
is greater than or equal to 1?

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:32.520 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:34.658 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: What if alpha is 1?

00:49:34.658 --> 00:49:36.200 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
Yeah, then you get 2.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:36.910 align:middle line:90%
But that's fine.

00:49:36.910 --> 00:49:39.440 align:middle line:90%


00:49:39.440 --> 00:49:41.640 align:middle line:90%
I just needed to show--

00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:47.880 align:middle line:84%
all I needed to do was
I needed to prove that--

00:49:47.880 --> 00:49:51.780 align:middle line:84%
I have that-- so you
see that I have that--

00:49:51.780 --> 00:49:55.800 align:middle line:84%
I'm assuming that this thing
here is strictly positive.

00:49:55.800 --> 00:49:58.280 align:middle line:90%
And then I define alpha 1.

00:49:58.280 --> 00:50:02.960 align:middle line:84%
But alpha 1 is strictly
less than alpha.

00:50:02.960 --> 00:50:06.160 align:middle line:84%
And then I have
that alpha squared--

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:09.360 align:middle line:84%
alpha 1 squared is
bigger or equal to 2.

00:50:09.360 --> 00:50:14.480 align:middle line:84%
This here means that alpha
1 is also an upper bound.

00:50:14.480 --> 00:50:17.200 align:middle line:84%
This is strictly
less than alpha.

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:20.220 align:middle line:84%
This was supposed to be
the least upper bound.

00:50:20.220 --> 00:50:22.960 align:middle line:90%
That's a contradiction, right?

00:50:22.960 --> 00:50:24.680 align:middle line:84%
And so, you see, I
fell into the trap.

00:50:24.680 --> 00:50:26.280 align:middle line:84%
I was doing it so
formally that I

00:50:26.280 --> 00:50:27.820 align:middle line:90%
lost track of what I was doing.

00:50:27.820 --> 00:50:30.000 align:middle line:84%
So I was actually in the
process of proving the--

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:33.960 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that's a danger
with-- but the formal proof is

00:50:33.960 --> 00:50:36.420 align:middle line:90%
much easier to read afterwards.

00:50:36.420 --> 00:50:41.640 align:middle line:84%
And so, you see, the difference
here with the formal proof was,

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:46.220 align:middle line:84%
last time, we did a
little calculation.

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:50.480 align:middle line:84%
And then we tried to figure
out, what should this h be?

00:50:50.480 --> 00:50:52.620 align:middle line:90%
And then it came at the end.

00:50:52.620 --> 00:50:56.020 align:middle line:84%
But when you write
down the formal proof,

00:50:56.020 --> 00:50:58.760 align:middle line:84%
then you would, up
front-- you would already

00:50:58.760 --> 00:51:00.440 align:middle line:84%
have done that
little calculation.

00:51:00.440 --> 00:51:05.160 align:middle line:84%
And you would, up front, say
what h was supposed to be.

00:51:05.160 --> 00:51:08.920 align:middle line:84%
And then you run
through the argument.

00:51:08.920 --> 00:51:09.720 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:51:09.720 --> 00:51:11.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Should
it say that alpha--

00:51:11.840 --> 00:51:15.723 align:middle line:90%
oh, I was looking [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:15.723 --> 00:51:16.640 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Sorry?

00:51:16.640 --> 00:51:18.598 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I was just
confused because I thought

00:51:18.598 --> 00:51:21.391 align:middle line:90%
that alpha was [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:21.391 --> 00:51:22.266 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Here?

00:51:22.266 --> 00:51:29.320 align:middle line:84%
So if-- I mean, of course,
alpha is much bigger than 1.

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:31.970 align:middle line:84%
But I'm just
using-- we already--

00:51:31.970 --> 00:51:35.810 align:middle line:84%
I only need here that alpha
is bigger or equal to 1

00:51:35.810 --> 00:51:38.150 align:middle line:84%
to say that this thing here
is bigger or equal to 2.

00:51:38.150 --> 00:51:40.010 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If you get
greater than 2, right?

00:51:40.010 --> 00:51:40.490 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Sorry?

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:41.510 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:41.510 --> 00:51:42.830 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: I think [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:42.830 --> 00:51:43.710 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: This is--

00:51:43.710 --> 00:51:44.210 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:51:44.210 --> 00:51:45.390 align:middle line:90%
This is alpha.

00:51:45.390 --> 00:51:49.390 align:middle line:84%
So the inequality here
is that alpha 1 squared

00:51:49.390 --> 00:51:51.430 align:middle line:90%
is bigger or equal to 2.

00:51:51.430 --> 00:51:55.670 align:middle line:84%
And I'm using that
alpha at this stage

00:51:55.670 --> 00:51:58.030 align:middle line:84%
here to conclude
this inequality.

00:51:58.030 --> 00:52:01.830 align:middle line:90%
I'm using-- sorry.

00:52:01.830 --> 00:52:03.010 align:middle line:90%
No, no, you're right.

00:52:03.010 --> 00:52:04.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sorry about that.

00:52:04.090 --> 00:52:04.632 align:middle line:90%
You're right.

00:52:04.632 --> 00:52:06.650 align:middle line:84%
I'm using that alpha--
no, I'm not using that.

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:10.030 align:middle line:84%
I'm using that alpha squared
is bigger or equal to 2.

00:52:10.030 --> 00:52:10.910 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, sorry.

00:52:10.910 --> 00:52:11.970 align:middle line:90%
That was what you meant.

00:52:11.970 --> 00:52:12.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:52:12.590 --> 00:52:14.710 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:52:14.710 --> 00:52:21.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that was a
formal proof of part 1.

00:52:21.990 --> 00:52:27.810 align:middle line:84%
And then there's part 2,
so the other inequality.

00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:30.830 align:middle line:90%


00:52:30.830 --> 00:52:34.590 align:middle line:90%
So how do we do that?

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:36.970 align:middle line:90%
And when you write this--

00:52:36.970 --> 00:52:39.910 align:middle line:90%


00:52:39.910 --> 00:52:43.790 align:middle line:84%
when you write this,
it's always good to try

00:52:43.790 --> 00:52:52.450 align:middle line:84%
to explain what you're going
to do, and in this case,

00:52:52.450 --> 00:52:54.370 align:middle line:84%
what is going to be
the contradiction.

00:52:54.370 --> 00:52:56.670 align:middle line:90%
So let's try to prove part 2.

00:52:56.670 --> 00:52:59.750 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, we get
it straight this time.

00:52:59.750 --> 00:53:04.470 align:middle line:84%
So part 2, so I
want to show that--

00:53:04.470 --> 00:53:09.230 align:middle line:84%
so we have-- part 1 was
establishing that alpha

00:53:09.230 --> 00:53:13.990 align:middle line:90%
squared was less or equal to 2.

00:53:13.990 --> 00:53:17.790 align:middle line:84%
Now we want to
prove-- so part 2,

00:53:17.790 --> 00:53:27.270 align:middle line:84%
we want to show that alpha
squared is bigger or equal to 2.

00:53:27.270 --> 00:53:29.990 align:middle line:90%


00:53:29.990 --> 00:53:36.390 align:middle line:84%
And so, again,
we're proving this--

00:53:36.390 --> 00:53:38.330 align:middle line:84%
we will show this
by contradiction.

00:53:38.330 --> 00:53:51.710 align:middle line:90%


00:53:51.710 --> 00:54:03.570 align:middle line:84%
So assume that alpha squared
is strictly less than 2.

00:54:03.570 --> 00:54:06.235 align:middle line:90%


00:54:06.235 --> 00:54:10.114 align:middle line:90%
And now it's--

00:54:10.114 --> 00:54:11.530 align:middle line:90%
I think it's helpful.

00:54:11.530 --> 00:54:13.210 align:middle line:84%
You don't necessarily
have to do it.

00:54:13.210 --> 00:54:17.030 align:middle line:84%
But I think it's
helpful if you say--

00:54:17.030 --> 00:54:19.450 align:middle line:90%
maybe it's too long.

00:54:19.450 --> 00:54:22.750 align:middle line:84%
But it's at least
helpful to think about,

00:54:22.750 --> 00:54:25.150 align:middle line:84%
where is the
contradiction coming from?

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:29.780 align:middle line:84%
So if alpha squared
is less than 2--

00:54:29.780 --> 00:54:31.375 align:middle line:90%
so I will say it.

00:54:31.375 --> 00:54:33.000 align:middle line:84%
You don't necessarily
have to write it.

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:56.248 align:middle line:84%
But indeed, we will show that
if this is the case, then

00:54:56.248 --> 00:54:56.790 align:middle line:90%
there exist--

00:54:56.790 --> 00:55:14.340 align:middle line:90%


00:55:14.340 --> 00:55:20.420 align:middle line:84%
there exist some numbers,
alpha 2, bigger than alpha,

00:55:20.420 --> 00:55:30.700 align:middle line:84%
such that alpha 2 squared
is also less than 2,

00:55:30.700 --> 00:55:49.100 align:middle line:84%
contradicting that alpha is
an upper bound for the set A

00:55:49.100 --> 00:55:50.140 align:middle line:90%
we defined.

00:55:50.140 --> 00:55:51.860 align:middle line:90%
That's what we will prove.

00:55:51.860 --> 00:55:55.570 align:middle line:90%


00:55:55.570 --> 00:56:02.290 align:middle line:84%
And so we want to find a real
number that is larger than this.

00:56:02.290 --> 00:56:05.500 align:middle line:90%


00:56:05.500 --> 00:56:12.020 align:middle line:84%
But still, the square is
still less than 2, OK?

00:56:12.020 --> 00:56:15.160 align:middle line:84%
And so, in this
case, I'm going to--

00:56:15.160 --> 00:56:19.624 align:middle line:90%


00:56:19.624 --> 00:56:21.900 align:middle line:90%
so now we do this--

00:56:21.900 --> 00:56:26.140 align:middle line:84%
the structure is
going to be the same.

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:31.460 align:middle line:84%
We had this little scrap paper
where we outlined the argument

00:56:31.460 --> 00:56:34.540 align:middle line:90%
and figure out what h had to be.

00:56:34.540 --> 00:56:37.180 align:middle line:90%
And so I'm going to use this h.

00:56:37.180 --> 00:56:39.220 align:middle line:90%
So we're going to, again--

00:56:39.220 --> 00:56:41.100 align:middle line:84%
maybe I'll just
erase this here so we

00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:44.280 align:middle line:84%
don't get confused with the
first part and the second part.

00:56:44.280 --> 00:56:54.320 align:middle line:90%


00:56:54.320 --> 00:56:54.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:54.820 --> 00:57:15.220 align:middle line:90%


00:57:15.220 --> 00:57:21.640 align:middle line:90%
OK, so I'm going to set h again.

00:57:21.640 --> 00:57:26.330 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to define it very
similar to what I did before.

00:57:26.330 --> 00:57:28.570 align:middle line:84%
But now I have to
remember that I'm

00:57:28.570 --> 00:57:32.210 align:middle line:84%
assuming that alpha
squared is less than 2.

00:57:32.210 --> 00:57:38.620 align:middle line:84%
So I define h to be 2 minus
alpha squared over 4 alpha.

00:57:38.620 --> 00:57:42.570 align:middle line:90%


00:57:42.570 --> 00:57:45.890 align:middle line:90%
This is how I define it.

00:57:45.890 --> 00:57:51.410 align:middle line:84%
And then what I'm interested
in is-- so I have here 0.

00:57:51.410 --> 00:57:54.770 align:middle line:84%
I have this that is supposed
to be the upper bound.

00:57:54.770 --> 00:57:58.110 align:middle line:84%
But I want to prove that that
really isn't an upper bound.

00:57:58.110 --> 00:58:04.830 align:middle line:84%
That's an element in my set A.
And so this is this alpha 2.

00:58:04.830 --> 00:58:08.170 align:middle line:84%
So I'm defining--
so I'm setting--

00:58:08.170 --> 00:58:16.890 align:middle line:84%
set this and alpha 2
equal to alpha plus h.

00:58:16.890 --> 00:58:18.270 align:middle line:84%
This here was just
to illustrate.

00:58:18.270 --> 00:58:21.150 align:middle line:84%
You don't necessarily
have to include that.

00:58:21.150 --> 00:58:23.950 align:middle line:90%


00:58:23.950 --> 00:58:26.170 align:middle line:90%
And I want to show--

00:58:26.170 --> 00:58:27.350 align:middle line:90%
we want to show--

00:58:27.350 --> 00:58:30.170 align:middle line:90%


00:58:30.170 --> 00:58:33.210 align:middle line:84%
I think it's a good idea to
write what you want to show.

00:58:33.210 --> 00:58:36.890 align:middle line:84%
In particular, if I really
had written that before,

00:58:36.890 --> 00:58:38.490 align:middle line:84%
then I wouldn't have
been in trouble,

00:58:38.490 --> 00:58:42.050 align:middle line:84%
because I was trying to
prove something else.

00:58:42.050 --> 00:58:48.570 align:middle line:84%
So you want to prove
that alpha squared here

00:58:48.570 --> 00:58:52.410 align:middle line:90%
is also less than 2.

00:58:52.410 --> 00:59:03.190 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so we already have
that alpha here is positive.

00:59:03.190 --> 00:59:10.530 align:middle line:90%


00:59:10.530 --> 00:59:13.170 align:middle line:90%
It's bigger than 1.

00:59:13.170 --> 00:59:17.850 align:middle line:84%
So this number here, this
here, we already know,

00:59:17.850 --> 00:59:19.090 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than alpha.

00:59:19.090 --> 00:59:23.410 align:middle line:90%


00:59:23.410 --> 00:59:26.450 align:middle line:90%
And so, if I can prove that--

00:59:26.450 --> 00:59:27.890 align:middle line:90%
so this here is--

00:59:27.890 --> 00:59:29.510 align:middle line:90%
so it's bigger than alpha.

00:59:29.510 --> 00:59:32.690 align:middle line:84%
If I can prove that the
square is less than 2,

00:59:32.690 --> 00:59:34.650 align:middle line:90%
then alpha here--

00:59:34.650 --> 00:59:37.630 align:middle line:84%
alpha here, sorry-- would
not be an upper bound.

00:59:37.630 --> 00:59:44.030 align:middle line:84%
There's another element in
the set A that is bigger.

00:59:44.030 --> 00:59:45.170 align:middle line:90%
So I want to prove that.

00:59:45.170 --> 00:59:49.910 align:middle line:84%
So now I'm looking
at alpha 2 squared.

00:59:49.910 --> 00:59:53.750 align:middle line:90%
So that is alpha plus h, right?

00:59:53.750 --> 00:59:55.930 align:middle line:90%
That's how I define alpha 2.

00:59:55.930 --> 00:59:57.110 align:middle line:90%
And I square it.

00:59:57.110 --> 01:00:00.090 align:middle line:90%


01:00:00.090 --> 01:00:02.290 align:middle line:84%
And if I do that,
then I get alpha

01:00:02.290 --> 01:00:12.660 align:middle line:84%
squared plus h squared
plus 2 h alpha.

01:00:12.660 --> 01:00:16.180 align:middle line:90%


01:00:16.180 --> 01:00:20.260 align:middle line:84%
And I now-- so now I
want an upper bound.

01:00:20.260 --> 01:00:26.480 align:middle line:84%
And so we already have that
alpha is this one here.

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:31.560 align:middle line:84%
h is-- you see that h
is, in this case here--

01:00:31.560 --> 01:00:38.600 align:middle line:84%
so h is equal to 2 minus
alpha squared over 4 alpha.

01:00:38.600 --> 01:00:42.240 align:middle line:90%
Alpha is bigger or equal to 1.

01:00:42.240 --> 01:00:45.640 align:middle line:84%
This here, the denominator,
is bounded by 2.

01:00:45.640 --> 01:00:47.180 align:middle line:90%
So again, it's 2 over 4.

01:00:47.180 --> 01:00:50.920 align:middle line:90%
So this is bounded by 1/2.

01:00:50.920 --> 01:00:54.340 align:middle line:90%
So h is positive.

01:00:54.340 --> 01:01:01.000 align:middle line:84%
And we have that h is positive
and h is less than 1/2, right?

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:06.040 align:middle line:84%
And so now, this
here, I can bound.

01:01:06.040 --> 01:01:10.520 align:middle line:84%
I can bound trivially by just
using that h is bounded by 1.

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:15.920 align:middle line:90%
So I get this plus h plus 2.

01:01:15.920 --> 01:01:22.920 align:middle line:84%
And then h times alpha,
again, or 2h alpha, this is--

01:01:22.920 --> 01:01:27.720 align:middle line:84%
when we multiply this by
2 alpha, then the alpha

01:01:27.720 --> 01:01:28.840 align:middle line:90%
cancel out.

01:01:28.840 --> 01:01:34.080 align:middle line:84%
And the 2 cancel
with one of these--

01:01:34.080 --> 01:01:35.360 align:middle line:90%
2 and this 4.

01:01:35.360 --> 01:01:39.140 align:middle line:84%
So you're getting 2 minus
alpha squared over 2.

01:01:39.140 --> 01:01:43.010 align:middle line:90%


01:01:43.010 --> 01:01:49.280 align:middle line:84%
And so now I get that this
thing here is bounded by--

01:01:49.280 --> 01:01:56.600 align:middle line:90%
so h here, h is also at--

01:01:56.600 --> 01:02:01.920 align:middle line:84%
a very rough bound for
h is using-- sorry--

01:02:01.920 --> 01:02:04.760 align:middle line:84%
so using-- so I
have that, and now

01:02:04.760 --> 01:02:16.920 align:middle line:84%
using that h here is equal to
alpha 2 minus alpha squared

01:02:16.920 --> 01:02:24.440 align:middle line:84%
over 2 over 4 alpha,
which is less than 2

01:02:24.440 --> 01:02:31.520 align:middle line:84%
minus alpha squared
over 2, since alpha here

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:34.180 align:middle line:90%
is bigger than 1, right?

01:02:34.180 --> 01:02:35.880 align:middle line:90%
So I have that.

01:02:35.880 --> 01:02:46.120 align:middle line:84%
So using that, we have
that alpha 2 squared

01:02:46.120 --> 01:02:49.120 align:middle line:84%
is less or equal to-- let
me just write that line.

01:02:49.120 --> 01:02:50.880 align:middle line:90%
I'm just now filling in.

01:02:50.880 --> 01:02:53.080 align:middle line:90%
Alpha squared, the H here--

01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:55.760 align:middle line:90%
I'm using this inequality here--

01:02:55.760 --> 01:02:59.120 align:middle line:90%
2 minus alpha squared over 2.

01:02:59.120 --> 01:03:03.160 align:middle line:84%
And then I have the
same thing again.

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:07.560 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this
here, it's this here times 2.

01:03:07.560 --> 01:03:15.400 align:middle line:84%
So this is just alpha squared
minus 2 plus 2 minus alpha

01:03:15.400 --> 01:03:15.900 align:middle line:90%
squared.

01:03:15.900 --> 01:03:19.230 align:middle line:90%


01:03:19.230 --> 01:03:24.030 align:middle line:84%
And this inequality here,
one of these inequalities, I

01:03:24.030 --> 01:03:26.690 align:middle line:84%
should have replaced
by a strict inequality.

01:03:26.690 --> 01:03:30.370 align:middle line:84%
This is because h is positive
and is strictly less than 1.

01:03:30.370 --> 01:03:32.630 align:middle line:84%
So this here is actually
a strict inequality.

01:03:32.630 --> 01:03:34.890 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a
strict inequality.

01:03:34.890 --> 01:03:37.650 align:middle line:90%


01:03:37.650 --> 01:03:42.750 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that this thing
here, the alpha cancel out.

01:03:42.750 --> 01:03:44.750 align:middle line:90%
And you're getting 2.

01:03:44.750 --> 01:03:50.350 align:middle line:84%
So you have that alpha 2
squared is strictly less than 2.

01:03:50.350 --> 01:03:52.630 align:middle line:90%
That's what we wanted to prove.

01:03:52.630 --> 01:04:07.150 align:middle line:84%
And this gives that alpha 2
is also in A. And yet, alpha 2

01:04:07.150 --> 01:04:10.750 align:middle line:90%
was bigger than alpha.

01:04:10.750 --> 01:04:13.130 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
desired contradiction.

01:04:13.130 --> 01:04:25.096 align:middle line:90%


01:04:25.096 --> 01:04:28.530 align:middle line:84%
So again, we already
did this last time.

01:04:28.530 --> 01:04:32.230 align:middle line:84%
But the point here
is that, how do you

01:04:32.230 --> 01:04:34.070 align:middle line:90%
write down a formal proof?

01:04:34.070 --> 01:04:36.030 align:middle line:84%
And a formal proof,
in this case,

01:04:36.030 --> 01:04:38.850 align:middle line:84%
is that you try-- very
clearly, in this case,

01:04:38.850 --> 01:04:41.390 align:middle line:90%
it was divided into two steps.

01:04:41.390 --> 01:04:45.330 align:middle line:84%
So you try to divide
it into the two steps.

01:04:45.330 --> 01:04:50.790 align:middle line:84%
And then maybe you have a
last line to say that part 1--

01:04:50.790 --> 01:05:06.670 align:middle line:84%
part 1 and part 2 together show
that alpha squared is equal

01:05:06.670 --> 01:05:09.210 align:middle line:90%
to 2, completing the proof.

01:05:09.210 --> 01:05:17.630 align:middle line:90%


01:05:17.630 --> 01:05:20.390 align:middle line:84%
And again, the point here
was that-- so we already

01:05:20.390 --> 01:05:21.890 align:middle line:90%
knew how to prove this.

01:05:21.890 --> 01:05:25.396 align:middle line:84%
But how do you write
down a formal proof?

01:05:25.396 --> 01:05:30.850 align:middle line:84%
And so, for this proof, it was
divided into these two steps.

01:05:30.850 --> 01:05:34.430 align:middle line:84%
So you try to write
each step separately.

01:05:34.430 --> 01:05:36.910 align:middle line:84%
They were both--
both of the two steps

01:05:36.910 --> 01:05:39.790 align:middle line:90%
was proven by contradiction.

01:05:39.790 --> 01:05:41.830 align:middle line:84%
And so you would
say up front-- you

01:05:41.830 --> 01:05:45.310 align:middle line:84%
would say that you're going
to prove it by contradiction.

01:05:45.310 --> 01:05:48.870 align:middle line:84%
And then, of course,
there would be--

01:05:48.870 --> 01:05:50.730 align:middle line:84%
the statement that
you want to prove--

01:05:50.730 --> 01:05:53.090 align:middle line:84%
since you're proving
it by contradiction,

01:05:53.090 --> 01:05:56.030 align:middle line:90%
you would assume the negation.

01:05:56.030 --> 01:05:59.930 align:middle line:84%
And then I think, if you can,
and it doesn't feel too much,

01:05:59.930 --> 01:06:03.925 align:middle line:84%
I think it's very helpful to
write what you are trying,

01:06:03.925 --> 01:06:06.050 align:middle line:84%
how you are trying to get
the contradiction, right?

01:06:06.050 --> 01:06:07.120 align:middle line:90%
That's what I tried here.

01:06:07.120 --> 01:06:09.650 align:middle line:90%


01:06:09.650 --> 01:06:11.900 align:middle line:84%
And then, you see,
then the big difference

01:06:11.900 --> 01:06:14.620 align:middle line:84%
from when we were trying to
figure out how to prove it

01:06:14.620 --> 01:06:19.820 align:middle line:84%
is that you now go ahead,
and you just define--

01:06:19.820 --> 01:06:21.220 align:middle line:90%
you define those things.

01:06:21.220 --> 01:06:24.440 align:middle line:90%
You define h and alpha 2, right?

01:06:24.440 --> 01:06:29.460 align:middle line:84%
That seems to come
out of nowhere.

01:06:29.460 --> 01:06:32.780 align:middle line:84%
And then you
establish the property

01:06:32.780 --> 01:06:35.740 align:middle line:84%
that you want to prove that
leads to the contradiction.

01:06:35.740 --> 01:06:39.500 align:middle line:90%
That's the structure.

01:06:39.500 --> 01:06:41.330 align:middle line:90%
Are there any questions to this?

01:06:41.330 --> 01:06:43.800 align:middle line:90%


01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:44.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:06:44.300 --> 01:06:50.670 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] property
of the real numbers [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:50.670 --> 01:06:52.500 align:middle line:90%
least upper bound [INAUDIBLE]?

01:06:52.500 --> 01:06:53.417 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

01:06:53.417 --> 01:06:55.340 align:middle line:90%
So we're using a few things.

01:06:55.340 --> 01:07:01.580 align:middle line:84%
We're using-- and we're
using a few things.

01:07:01.580 --> 01:07:05.100 align:middle line:90%
We're using that it's ordered.

01:07:05.100 --> 01:07:09.900 align:middle line:84%
We're also using something about
that it's an ordered field.

01:07:09.900 --> 01:07:10.608 align:middle line:90%
And why?

01:07:10.608 --> 01:07:12.150 align:middle line:84%
Because we're using
something-- well,

01:07:12.150 --> 01:07:14.260 align:middle line:84%
we're using something
about multiplication

01:07:14.260 --> 01:07:16.360 align:middle line:90%
to at all define square root.

01:07:16.360 --> 01:07:21.220 align:middle line:84%
And also, we're using something
about that 1 is bigger than 0.

01:07:21.220 --> 01:07:30.940 align:middle line:90%


01:07:30.940 --> 01:07:33.940 align:middle line:84%
And then-- so we're using--
and then we're also using,

01:07:33.940 --> 01:07:37.100 align:middle line:84%
of course, completeness in
order to define this least

01:07:37.100 --> 01:07:38.140 align:middle line:90%
upper bound.

01:07:38.140 --> 01:07:41.420 align:middle line:84%
So we're using a
bunch of these things.

01:07:41.420 --> 01:07:44.740 align:middle line:90%
But of course, if you have--

01:07:44.740 --> 01:07:47.100 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:07:47.100 --> 01:07:49.860 align:middle line:90%
I mean, if you're asking when--

01:07:49.860 --> 01:07:52.900 align:middle line:90%
and that's not really--

01:07:52.900 --> 01:07:59.020 align:middle line:84%
at this stage, very, very soon,
in one of the next few lectures,

01:07:59.020 --> 01:08:01.700 align:middle line:84%
things will be in
the real numbers.

01:08:01.700 --> 01:08:04.020 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to
work on general fields.

01:08:04.020 --> 01:08:06.020 align:middle line:90%
And we're not going to-- yeah.

01:08:06.020 --> 01:08:08.500 align:middle line:84%
General fields-- this is
not part of this topic.

01:08:08.500 --> 01:08:13.220 align:middle line:84%
But of course, it's
interesting to ask.

01:08:13.220 --> 01:08:15.100 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
your point, is

01:08:15.100 --> 01:08:17.340 align:middle line:84%
like, when can you
define something

01:08:17.340 --> 01:08:20.260 align:middle line:84%
like a square root
of 2 in a field?

01:08:20.260 --> 01:08:21.340 align:middle line:90%
Or something like that.

01:08:21.340 --> 01:08:22.600 align:middle line:90%
And there's a lot of things.

01:08:22.600 --> 01:08:24.100 align:middle line:84%
You're absolutely
right that there's

01:08:24.100 --> 01:08:27.979 align:middle line:84%
a lot of these things that
was just general property.

01:08:27.979 --> 01:08:30.279 align:middle line:84%
But maybe we shouldn't
get too much into that.

01:08:30.279 --> 01:08:33.340 align:middle line:90%


01:08:33.340 --> 01:08:35.620 align:middle line:90%
So I wanted to--

01:08:35.620 --> 01:08:39.100 align:middle line:84%
there's a few more things
I was hoping to do.

01:08:39.100 --> 01:08:44.859 align:middle line:84%
So I also wanted to just talk
about the Archimedean property

01:08:44.859 --> 01:08:45.859 align:middle line:90%
again.

01:08:45.859 --> 01:08:56.399 align:middle line:84%
And so I wanted to just outline
how to write a formal proof.

01:08:56.399 --> 01:09:01.620 align:middle line:84%
And the reason, of course,
why I'm illustrating how to

01:09:01.620 --> 01:09:03.620 align:middle line:90%
write a formal--

01:09:03.620 --> 01:09:07.170 align:middle line:84%
writing a formal proof is an
important part of this class.

01:09:07.170 --> 01:09:12.010 align:middle line:84%
And I'm obviously
using the things

01:09:12.010 --> 01:09:15.490 align:middle line:84%
that we already proved
last time, just so

01:09:15.490 --> 01:09:17.676 align:middle line:90%
that you can focus on how--

01:09:17.676 --> 01:09:20.729 align:middle line:84%
not to prove-- not
the statements,

01:09:20.729 --> 01:09:25.689 align:middle line:84%
why the statements should be
true, but just how to write it.

01:09:25.689 --> 01:09:31.660 align:middle line:84%
And so let's talk about
the Archimedean property.

01:09:31.660 --> 01:09:37.850 align:middle line:90%


01:09:37.850 --> 01:09:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And so the Archimedean
property, just saying that--

01:09:41.770 --> 01:09:49.010 align:middle line:84%
so this is the theorem that
the natural numbers is not

01:09:49.010 --> 01:09:50.019 align:middle line:90%
bounded from above.

01:09:50.019 --> 01:09:59.050 align:middle line:90%


01:09:59.050 --> 01:10:01.090 align:middle line:84%
That's one way of
formulating it.

01:10:01.090 --> 01:10:03.670 align:middle line:84%
You could also say,
like we did last time,

01:10:03.670 --> 01:10:05.970 align:middle line:84%
that whenever you
take a real, there's

01:10:05.970 --> 01:10:10.050 align:middle line:84%
a larger natural
number than that real.

01:10:10.050 --> 01:10:12.950 align:middle line:90%
But that's the same.

01:10:12.950 --> 01:10:13.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:13.450 --> 01:10:15.310 align:middle line:90%
So now, how do we prove this?

01:10:15.310 --> 01:10:19.370 align:middle line:90%


01:10:19.370 --> 01:10:21.450 align:middle line:84%
So again, here, we're
thinking about things

01:10:21.450 --> 01:10:24.850 align:middle line:84%
as being subset
of R. We always--

01:10:24.850 --> 01:10:28.370 align:middle line:84%
when we don't really
mention it, then we always

01:10:28.370 --> 01:10:35.530 align:middle line:84%
think about it as being subset
of R. And so we will prove--

01:10:35.530 --> 01:10:37.430 align:middle line:84%
we will show this
by contradiction--

01:10:37.430 --> 01:10:44.370 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.370 --> 01:10:45.510 align:middle line:90%
by contradiction.

01:10:45.510 --> 01:10:49.210 align:middle line:90%


01:10:49.210 --> 01:11:02.920 align:middle line:84%
So suppose alpha is an upper
bound for the natural numbers.

01:11:02.920 --> 01:11:05.730 align:middle line:90%


01:11:05.730 --> 01:11:22.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, we can assume, after
replacing alpha by sup of A,

01:11:22.290 --> 01:11:33.900 align:middle line:84%
we can assume that alpha
is the least upper bound.

01:11:33.900 --> 01:11:43.650 align:middle line:90%


01:11:43.650 --> 01:11:48.730 align:middle line:84%
And now-- and then I
think it's nice, again,

01:11:48.730 --> 01:11:54.860 align:middle line:84%
to write where the
contradiction is coming from.

01:11:54.860 --> 01:12:02.010 align:middle line:90%


01:12:02.010 --> 01:12:33.890 align:middle line:84%
So we'll show-- we will get the
desired contradiction by showing

01:12:33.890 --> 01:12:50.370 align:middle line:84%
that alpha minus 1 is also
an upper bound, contradicting

01:12:50.370 --> 01:12:53.910 align:middle line:84%
that alpha was the
least upper bound.

01:12:53.910 --> 01:13:03.860 align:middle line:90%


01:13:03.860 --> 01:13:11.180 align:middle line:90%
And so now, since alpha--

01:13:11.180 --> 01:13:14.440 align:middle line:84%
so this is what
we want to prove.

01:13:14.440 --> 01:13:32.880 align:middle line:84%
Since alpha is an upper bound
for all natural numbers,

01:13:32.880 --> 01:13:35.000 align:middle line:84%
if you add 1 to
the natural number,

01:13:35.000 --> 01:13:39.200 align:middle line:84%
this is also-- this here is
also a natural number, right?

01:13:39.200 --> 01:13:41.300 align:middle line:84%
n plus 1 is also
a natural number.

01:13:41.300 --> 01:13:46.820 align:middle line:84%
So n plus 1 must be less or
equal to this upper bound.

01:13:46.820 --> 01:13:50.000 align:middle line:90%


01:13:50.000 --> 01:14:01.120 align:middle line:90%
But this implies that n--

01:14:01.120 --> 01:14:05.280 align:middle line:84%
subtracting 1 on both sides
implies that n is less or equal

01:14:05.280 --> 01:14:09.120 align:middle line:90%
to alpha minus 1, and this--

01:14:09.120 --> 01:14:20.260 align:middle line:84%
which holds for all n,
all natural numbers.

01:14:20.260 --> 01:14:26.620 align:middle line:84%
So alpha minus 1 is
also an upper bound.

01:14:26.620 --> 01:14:40.960 align:middle line:90%


01:14:40.960 --> 01:14:41.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:41.640 --> 01:14:48.720 align:middle line:84%
And this proof gives you
the desired contradiction.

01:14:48.720 --> 01:14:52.720 align:middle line:84%
So that's how you
would write that.

01:14:52.720 --> 01:14:57.360 align:middle line:84%
Let me talk a little
bit about sequences.

01:14:57.360 --> 01:15:00.440 align:middle line:90%
So this will be a big topic.

01:15:00.440 --> 01:15:01.660 align:middle line:90%
So sequences.

01:15:01.660 --> 01:15:06.600 align:middle line:90%


01:15:06.600 --> 01:15:09.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, first-- so we talked
about that a little bit.

01:15:09.180 --> 01:15:22.640 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at the-- so how
do we think about square root

01:15:22.640 --> 01:15:26.340 align:middle line:90%
2 on the real line?

01:15:26.340 --> 01:15:30.040 align:middle line:84%
So the way to think about square
root of 2 is what we did here--

01:15:30.040 --> 01:15:34.340 align:middle line:84%
that is, this positive thing
so that the square is 2.

01:15:34.340 --> 01:15:39.960 align:middle line:84%
But if you want to place square
root of 2 on the real line,

01:15:39.960 --> 01:15:46.060 align:middle line:84%
then you could think about it
as 1 as a limit of a sequence.

01:15:46.060 --> 01:15:51.280 align:middle line:84%
If you take 1, and then
the 1 is less than 1.4,

01:15:51.280 --> 01:16:02.990 align:middle line:84%
which is less than 1.41, which
is less than 1.414, et cetera.

01:16:02.990 --> 01:16:07.590 align:middle line:90%
And so this here is a sequence.

01:16:07.590 --> 01:16:10.050 align:middle line:84%
I'll make that precise
in just a minute,

01:16:10.050 --> 01:16:13.110 align:middle line:84%
but an increasing
sequence of numbers.

01:16:13.110 --> 01:16:17.210 align:middle line:84%
And the limit is
square root of 2.

01:16:17.210 --> 01:16:21.470 align:middle line:84%
So if you plug square root
of 2 in on the calculator,

01:16:21.470 --> 01:16:23.370 align:middle line:84%
it will bring out
a lot of digits.

01:16:23.370 --> 01:16:24.970 align:middle line:90%
And these are the first digits.

01:16:24.970 --> 01:16:27.070 align:middle line:90%
And it will continue on.

01:16:27.070 --> 01:16:30.270 align:middle line:84%
And that's how you think
about square root of 2

01:16:30.270 --> 01:16:34.670 align:middle line:84%
if you want to think
about it on the real line.

01:16:34.670 --> 01:16:36.750 align:middle line:90%
And so we want to--

01:16:36.750 --> 01:16:40.870 align:middle line:84%
and so square root of 2 is
going to be the limit of these.

01:16:40.870 --> 01:16:42.570 align:middle line:84%
And we need to
make this precise.

01:16:42.570 --> 01:16:48.990 align:middle line:84%
And we also need to make precise
what, really, a sequence is.

01:16:48.990 --> 01:17:05.740 align:middle line:84%
So a sequence-- so a
sequence of real numbers--

01:17:05.740 --> 01:17:13.750 align:middle line:90%


01:17:13.750 --> 01:17:14.720 align:middle line:90%
this is a map.

01:17:14.720 --> 01:17:17.310 align:middle line:90%


01:17:17.310 --> 01:17:24.630 align:middle line:84%
It's a function from the
natural numbers into R.

01:17:24.630 --> 01:17:29.910 align:middle line:84%
So for each natural number,
you get a real number.

01:17:29.910 --> 01:17:35.150 align:middle line:90%
And so a function--

01:17:35.150 --> 01:17:39.990 align:middle line:84%
a function is defined by the
value at different points.

01:17:39.990 --> 01:17:42.690 align:middle line:90%
So this thing here--

01:17:42.690 --> 01:17:46.610 align:middle line:84%
but if you want to think
about it as a sequence,

01:17:46.610 --> 01:17:51.870 align:middle line:84%
then it's common to denote it--
to denote this here like that.

01:17:51.870 --> 01:17:55.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is how one typically
writes a sequence, where,

01:17:55.430 --> 01:18:03.570 align:middle line:84%
instead of what the argument is,
what this is, inside a bracket,

01:18:03.570 --> 01:18:07.000 align:middle line:90%
you write it as a subscript.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:10.150 align:middle line:90%
So this is a sequence.

01:18:10.150 --> 01:18:15.550 align:middle line:84%
And so, in the case
over there, if you're

01:18:15.550 --> 01:18:20.470 align:middle line:84%
thinking about a1,
say, to be equal to 1,

01:18:20.470 --> 01:18:25.830 align:middle line:90%
a2 to be equal to 1.4, a3--

01:18:25.830 --> 01:18:28.830 align:middle line:84%
and now I'm thinking
about the sequence here.

01:18:28.830 --> 01:18:31.790 align:middle line:84%
As I'm thinking about
square root of 2,

01:18:31.790 --> 01:18:36.470 align:middle line:84%
and I take the number
of the subscript here,

01:18:36.470 --> 01:18:39.870 align:middle line:84%
I'm just taking the number of
digits in square root of 2.

01:18:39.870 --> 01:18:41.630 align:middle line:90%
So now I need three digits.

01:18:41.630 --> 01:18:46.310 align:middle line:90%
Here, I need a 2, 1, 4, 1.

01:18:46.310 --> 01:18:53.920 align:middle line:90%
a4 is 1.414, et cetera.

01:18:53.920 --> 01:18:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And so then you have--
so then a n here

01:18:58.540 --> 01:19:05.780 align:middle line:90%
is a sequence of real numbers.

01:19:05.780 --> 01:19:07.700 align:middle line:90%
And it's actually increasing--

01:19:07.700 --> 01:19:12.300 align:middle line:84%
that the sequence a n
is less than a n plus 1.

01:19:12.300 --> 01:19:14.540 align:middle line:90%
We have this property.

01:19:14.540 --> 01:19:20.620 align:middle line:84%
And we want to talk about-- next
time, we want to talk about,

01:19:20.620 --> 01:19:23.100 align:middle line:90%
what does a limit mean?

01:19:23.100 --> 01:19:24.670 align:middle line:90%
What is a limit?

01:19:24.670 --> 01:19:27.380 align:middle line:90%


01:19:27.380 --> 01:19:31.780 align:middle line:84%
And so square root
of 2, indeed, will

01:19:31.780 --> 01:19:33.880 align:middle line:90%
be the limit of this sequence.

01:19:33.880 --> 01:19:36.500 align:middle line:84%
And the limit, you write
like this, sometimes,

01:19:36.500 --> 01:19:40.940 align:middle line:90%
as n goes to infinity of a n.

01:19:40.940 --> 01:19:43.810 align:middle line:84%
But we'll talk about
this next time.

01:19:43.810 --> 01:19:47.000 align:middle line:90%